@page "/components/data-display/badge/accessibility"
@layout MainLayout
@using Sunfish.UIAdapters.Blazor.Components.Showcase

<PageTitle>Badge / Accessibility · Sunfish Kitchen Sink</PageTitle>

<SunfishExamplePanel Title="Badge / Accessibility"
                     Breadcrumb="@_breadcrumb"
                     GitHubUrl="https://github.com/ctwoodwa/Sunfish/blob/main/apps/kitchen-sink/Pages/Components/DataDisplay/Badge/Accessibility/Demo.razor"
                     Sources="@GeneratedSources">

    <Narrative>
        <p>
            <code>SunfishBadge</code> renders a <code>&lt;span&gt;</code> with no implicit ARIA role, so
            accessibility is about pairing meaning with the anchor element. A count badge next to an
            Inbox button should read as "Inbox, 3 unread" — not "Inbox" followed by a decorative "3". A
            status dot on an avatar should communicate presence (online/offline/busy) without relying on
            color alone.
        </p>
        <p>
            The recommended patterns below use <code>aria-label</code> on the wrapper to combine the
            trigger text with the badge meaning, or <code>role="status"</code> on the badge itself when
            it represents a live, standalone state value.
        </p>
    </Narrative>

    <Example>
        <div style="display:flex; flex-direction:column; gap:1.25rem;">
            <div class="demo-row" style="align-items:center; gap:1.5rem;">
                <div style="position:relative;display:inline-flex;"
                     aria-label="Inbox, 3 unread messages">
                    <SunfishButton Variant="ButtonVariant.Secondary" aria-hidden="true">Inbox</SunfishButton>
                    <SunfishBadge Variant="BadgeVariant.Danger" Position="edge" aria-hidden="true">3</SunfishBadge>
                </div>
                <span>Wrapper <code>aria-label</code> merges trigger and count — badge marked <code>aria-hidden</code>.</span>
            </div>

            <div class="demo-row" style="align-items:center; gap:1.5rem;">
                <div style="position:relative;display:inline-flex;">
                    <SunfishAvatar Initials="PW" />
                    <SunfishBadge Variant="BadgeVariant.Success"
                                  Position="edge"
                                  HorizontalAlign="end"
                                  VerticalAlign="bottom"
                                  ShowCutoutBorder="true"
                                  role="status"
                                  aria-label="Online" />
                </div>
                <span>Status dot — <code>role="status"</code> + <code>aria-label</code> carry the meaning without relying on color.</span>
            </div>

            <div class="demo-row" style="align-items:center; gap:1.5rem;">
                <SunfishBadge Variant="BadgeVariant.Warning" role="status">Degraded</SunfishBadge>
                <span>Standalone status — badge itself carries <code>role="status"</code>; the visible text is already announced.</span>
            </div>

            <dl style="font-size:0.875rem; max-width:640px;">
                <dt><strong>Pairing with a trigger</strong></dt>
                <dd>Put <code>aria-label</code> on the wrapping container; mark the badge <code>aria-hidden="true"</code>.</dd>
                <dt><strong>Standalone status</strong></dt>
                <dd>Add <code>role="status"</code> so screen readers treat the badge as a live region.</dd>
                <dt><strong>Don't rely on color</strong></dt>
                <dd>Danger / Warning / Success variants use color — pair them with text or an <code>aria-label</code>.</dd>
                <dt><strong>Contrast</strong></dt>
                <dd>All variants meet WCAG AA non-text contrast (3:1) against their default surface; verify custom palettes.</dd>
                <dt><strong>Keyboard</strong></dt>
                <dd>Badges are not focusable. Focus moves to the associated control (button, link, avatar).</dd>
            </dl>
        </div>
    </Example>

</SunfishExamplePanel>

@code {
    private static readonly string[] _breadcrumb =
        ["Components", "Data Display", "Badge", "Accessibility"];
}
